<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n36095b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n36" href="#n36095b">N36 (VI.B.29)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n36all.htm#n36095b"> 95(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> drenching the cattle</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[Gerard Boate, in his <cite>Natural History of Ireland</cite> (1652)]</font>: &ldquo;The brooks&mdash;beside the great good they do the land in watering the same, and beside the commodity they afford of <mark>drenching the cattle</mark> and other beasts&mdash;do also greatly serve the inhabitants for another good use&mdash;to wit, the grinding of the corn, whereunto the windmills are very little used in Ireland, because they have the conveniency, through the great number of brooks, to erect watermills in every quarter where it is necessary: which brings a great profit to the owners being kept and maintained with less cost and labour.&rdquo; <small> Weston St. John Joyce, <a name="WSJ1" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#WSJ1"><cite title="source">The Neighbourhood of Dublin</cite></a> (1921) 111</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
